Kugelann, 
<number id="FE02DB5BFFA2FFF1FEEB17175E899379" box="[369,424,1572,1593]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" value="1794.0">1794</number>
: 
<number id="FE02DB5BFFA2FFF1FE2D17105EFC9379" box="[439,477,1571,1593]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" value="578.0">578</number>
</taxonomicName>
(
<typeStatus id="977177DEFFA2FFF1FE7017175D369379" box="[490,535,1572,1593]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">type</typeStatus>
species 
<taxonomicName id="8FCAB2FFFFA2FFF1FDF417175B219379" authority="Kugelann 1794: 579" authorityName="Kugelann" authorityPageNumber="579" authorityYear="1794" box="[622,1024,1571,1594]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="riparia">
<emphasis id="7ABE156EFFA2FFF1FDF417175C00937A" box="[622,801,1572,1594]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Hydraena riparia</emphasis>
Kugelann 
<number id="FE02DB5BFFA2FFF1FC0A17175CE79379" box="[912,966,1572,1593]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" value="1794.0">1794</number>
: 
<number id="FE02DB5BFFA2FFF1FC4C17105B219379" box="[982,1024,1571,1593]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" value="579.0">579</number>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4875C97CFFA2FFF1FF0D17555E669272" blockId="12.[151,1437,1638,2023]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
The speciose, cosmopolitan genus 
<taxonomicName id="8FCAB2FFFFA2FFF1FDBF17555DB4933E" box="[549,661,1638,1662]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="7ABE156EFFA2FFF1FDBF17555DB4933E" box="[549,661,1638,1662]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Hydraena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is well defined by the following autapomorphic characteristics: 
<number id="FE02DB5BFFA2FFF1FA1F17555AB0933E" box="[1413,1425,1638,1662]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" value="1.0">1</number>
) presence of a labral-mandibular interlocking device (
<bibRefCitation id="2C5BB48DFFA2FFF1FD6F17B95CB193E2" author="Perkins" box="[757,912,1674,1698]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" refString="Perkins, P. D. (1989). Adelphydraena, new genus, and two new species from Venezuela, and remarks on phylogenetic relationships within the subtribe Hydraenina (Coleoptera: Hydraenidae). Proceedings of the Biological Society of Washington, 102, 447 - 457." type="journal article" year="1989">
Perkins 
<number id="FE02DB5BFFA2FFF1FCCE17B95CB193E2" box="[852,912,1674,1698]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" value="1989.0">1989</number>
</bibRefCitation>
), 
<number id="FE02DB5BFFA2FFF1FC3C17B95C9493E2" box="[934,949,1674,1698]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" value="2.0">2</number>
) mentum with an acute median projection anteriorly (
<bibRefCitation id="2C5BB48DFFA2FFF1FE89179D5E8F9386" author="Perkins" box="[275,430,1710,1734]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" refString="Perkins, P. D. (1989). Adelphydraena, new genus, and two new species from Venezuela, and remarks on phylogenetic relationships within the subtribe Hydraenina (Coleoptera: Hydraenidae). Proceedings of the Biological Society of Washington, 102, 447 - 457." type="journal article" year="1989">
Perkins 
<number id="FE02DB5BFFA2FFF1FEE8179D5E8F9386" box="[370,430,1710,1734]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" value="1989.0">1989</number>
</bibRefCitation>
), 
<number id="FE02DB5BFFA2FFF1FE59179D5EF09386" box="[451,465,1710,1734]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" value="3.0">3</number>
) various complex sensilla (
<bibRefCitation id="2C5BB48DFFA2FFF1FC91179D5C859386" author="Perkins" box="[779,932,1710,1734]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" refString="Perkins, P. D. (1997). Life on the effective bubble: exocrine secretion delivery systems (ESDS) and the evolution and classification of beetles in the family Hydraenidae (Insecta: Coleoptera). Annals of Carnegie Museum, 66 (2), 89 - 207." type="journal article" year="1997">
Perkins 
<number id="FE02DB5BFFA2FFF1FCF3179D5C859386" box="[873,932,1710,1734]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" value="1997.0">1997</number>
</bibRefCitation>
), and 
<number id="FE02DB5BFFA2FFF1FC71179D5CDB9386" box="[1003,1018,1710,1734]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" value="4.0">4</number>
) specialized features of the exocrine secretion delivery system (
<bibRefCitation id="2C5BB48DFFA2FFF1FE5717E15D4893AA" author="Perkins" box="[461,617,1746,1770]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" refString="Perkins, P. D. (1997). Life on the effective bubble: exocrine secretion delivery systems (ESDS) and the evolution and classification of beetles in the family Hydraenidae (Insecta: Coleoptera). Annals of Carnegie Museum, 66 (2), 89 - 207." type="journal article" year="1997">
Perkins 
<number id="FE02DB5BFFA2FFF1FDB717E15D4893AA" box="[557,617,1746,1770]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" value="1997.0">1997</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). There is general agreement among current workers that 
<taxonomicName id="8FCAB2FFFFA2FFF1FA9517E05A5E93AB" box="[1295,1407,1747,1771]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="7ABE156EFFA2FFF1FA9517E05A5E93AB" box="[1295,1407,1747,1771]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Hydraena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is monophyletic, based on these characters (for example, 
<bibRefCitation id="2C5BB48DFFA2FFF1FC9017C55CE3924E" author="Jach" box="[778,962,1782,1806]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" refString="Jach, M. A., Beutel, R., Diaz, J. A. &amp; Kodada, J. (2000). Subgeneric classification, descriptions of head structures, and world check list of Hydraena Kugelann (Insecta: Coleoptera: Hydraenidae). Annalen des Naturhistorischen Museums in Wien, 102 B, 177 - 258." type="journal article" year="2000">
Jäch et al. 
<number id="FE02DB5BFFA2FFF1FC1F17C55CE3924E" box="[901,962,1782,1806]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" value="2000.0">2000</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). The South American species meet these generic criteria.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4875C97CFFA2FFF0FF5D160D5AA69424" blockId="12.[151,1437,1638,2023]" lastBlockId="13.[151,1436,151,751]" lastPageId="13" lastPageNumber="14" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
The division of 
<taxonomicName id="8FCAB2FFFFA2FFF1FEE6160D5ECD9216" box="[380,492,1854,1878]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="7ABE156EFFA2FFF1FEE6160D5ECD9216" box="[380,492,1854,1878]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Hydraena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
into subgenera is currently a matter of uncertainty. Some groupings of species into large putative monophyletic groups is more certain, but the basal relationships among the major clades, based on recently published 
<collectionCode id="2EDB51B9FFA2FFF1FEEA16B45E8C92DF" LSID="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15536" box="[368,429,1927,1951]" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15536" name="Department of Natural Resources, Environment, The Arts and Sport" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">DNA</collectionCode>
analysis, are not well supported (
<bibRefCitation id="2C5BB48DFFA2FFF1FCAA16B55B2592DE" author="Ribera" box="[816,1028,1926,1951]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" refString="Ribera, I, Castro, A., Diaz, J. A., Garrido, J., Izquierdo, A., Jach, M. A., Valladares, L. F. (2011). The geography of speciation in narrow-range endemics of the ' Haenydra' lineage (Coleoptera, Hydraenidae, Hydraena). Journal of Biogeography 38, 502 - 516." type="journal article" year="2011">
Ribera 
<emphasis id="7ABE156EFFA2FFF1FC1C16BB5CE092DE" box="[902,961,1926,1951]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">et al.</emphasis>
<number id="FE02DB5BFFA2FFF1FC5316B55B2592DE" box="[969,1028,1926,1950]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" value="2011.0">2011</number>
</bibRefCitation>
: 
<number id="FE02DB5BFFA2FFF1FB8016B55B6992DE" box="[1050,1096,1926,1950]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" value="508.0">508</number>
). The morphological cladistic analysis of 
<bibRefCitation id="2C5BB48DFFA2FFF1FE8716995ECB9282" box="[285,490,1962,1987]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" refString="Jach, M. A., Beutel, R., Diaz, J. A. &amp; Kodada, J. (2000). Subgeneric classification, descriptions of head structures, and world check list of Hydraena Kugelann (Insecta: Coleoptera: Hydraenidae). Annalen des Naturhistorischen Museums in Wien, 102 B, 177 - 258." type="journal article">
Jäch 
<emphasis id="7ABE156EFFA2FFF1FEC3169F5EB49283" box="[345,405,1963,1987]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">et al.</emphasis>
(
<number id="FE02DB5BFFA2FFF1FE3D16995EC39282" box="[423,482,1962,1986]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" value="2000.0">2000</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
concluded that &quot;the great phylogenetic alternative&quot; to 
<taxonomicName id="8FCAB2FFFFA2FFF1FBF216985BF99283" box="[1128,1240,1963,1987]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="7ABE156EFFA2FFF1FBF216985BF99283" box="[1128,1240,1963,1987]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Hydraena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<emphasis id="7ABE156EFFA2FFF1FB76169F5BD69283" box="[1260,1271,1964,1987]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">s</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="7ABE156EFFA2FFF1FB67169F5A389283" box="[1277,1305,1964,1987]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">str</emphasis>
.) had been found in 
<taxonomicName id="8FCAB2FFFFA2FFF1FF6416FD5E4F92A6" box="[254,366,1998,2022]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="7ABE156EFFA2FFF1FF6416FD5E4F92A6" box="[254,366,1998,2022]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Hydraena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="8FCAB2FFFFA2FFF1FEE516FD5D3A92A6" box="[383,539,1998,2022]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraenopsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="7ABE156EFFA2FFF1FEE516FD5D3A92A6" box="[383,539,1998,2022]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Hydraenopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). At least some of the South American species of 
<taxonomicName id="8FCAB2FFFFA2FFF1FBC216FD5BE992A6" box="[1112,1224,1998,2022]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="7ABE156EFFA2FFF1FBC216FD5BE992A6" box="[1112,1224,1998,2022]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Hydraena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are most probably related to species placed by Jäch 
<emphasis id="7ABE156EFFA3FFF0FD8111AA5D7495F0" box="[539,597,152,176]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">et al.</emphasis>
in 
<taxonomicName id="8FCAB2FFFFA3FFF0FDE511AB5DCE95F0" box="[639,751,152,176]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="7ABE156EFFA3FFF0FDE511AB5DCE95F0" box="[639,751,152,176]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Hydraena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="8FCAB2FFFFA3FFF0FC9811AB5CBF95F0" box="[770,926,152,176]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraenopsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="7ABE156EFFA3FFF0FC9811AB5CBF95F0" box="[770,926,152,176]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Hydraenopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). However, the 
<collectionCode id="2EDB51B9FFA3FFF0FBC011AB5BB695F0" LSID="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15536" box="[1114,1175,152,176]" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15536" name="Department of Natural Resources, Environment, The Arts and Sport" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">DNA</collectionCode>
study by Ribera 
<emphasis id="7ABE156EFFA3FFF0FAFB11AA5ABD95F0" box="[1377,1436,152,176]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">et al.</emphasis>
included only one unidentified South American species (from the famous 
<taxonomicName id="8FCAB2FFFFA3FFF0FC40118F5B1D9594" box="[986,1084,188,212]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="107" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tobogan">Tobogan</taxonomicName>
locality), probably of the 
<emphasis id="7ABE156EFFA3FFF0FAF9118E5FDE95B8" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Marginicollis</emphasis>
Group. More 
<collectionCode id="2EDB51B9FFA3FFF0FE3711D35ECB95B8" LSID="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15536" box="[429,490,224,248]" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15536" name="Department of Natural Resources, Environment, The Arts and Sport" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">DNA</collectionCode>
studies are needed, especially of the unusual 
<taxonomicName id="8FCAB2FFFFA3FFF0FC6C11D25B5395B8" box="[1014,1138,225,248]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="paeminosa">
<emphasis id="7ABE156EFFA3FFF0FC6C11D25B5395B8" box="[1014,1138,225,248]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Paeminosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="8FCAB2FFFFA3FFF0FB1911D35BC395B7" box="[1155,1250,224,247]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="82" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="curvosa">
<emphasis id="7ABE156EFFA3FFF0FB1911D35BC395B7" box="[1155,1250,224,247]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Curvosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="8FCAB2FFFFA3FFF0FAB911D35ABD95B8" box="[1315,1436,224,248]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="86" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="multispina">
<emphasis id="7ABE156EFFA3FFF0FAB911D35ABD95B8" box="[1315,1436,224,248]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Multispina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Groups, to better understand the relationships of South American 
<taxonomicName id="8FCAB2FFFFA3FFF0FC0910375B22945C" box="[915,1027,260,284]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="7ABE156EFFA3FFF0FC0910375B22945C" box="[915,1027,260,284]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Hydraena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. For now, I prefer not to formally assign species to subgenera until more results of 
<collectionCode id="2EDB51B9FFA3FFF0FD5F101B5C239400" LSID="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15536" box="[709,770,296,320]" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15536" name="Department of Natural Resources, Environment, The Arts and Sport" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">DNA</collectionCode>
analysis are published, and it is shown that all species are monophyletic, and that &quot; 
<taxonomicName id="8FCAB2FFFFA3FFF0FE31107F5D669424" box="[427,583,332,356]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraenopsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="7ABE156EFFA3FFF0FE31107F5D669424" box="[427,583,332,356]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Hydraenopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
&quot; is definitely not nested within what is now considered 
<taxonomicName id="8FCAB2FFFFA3FFF0FB21107F5A0A9424" box="[1211,1323,332,356]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="7ABE156EFFA3FFF0FB21107F5A0A9424" box="[1211,1323,332,356]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Hydraena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<emphasis id="7ABE156EFFA3FFF0FAA1107E5A679424" box="[1339,1350,333,356]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">s</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="7ABE156EFFA3FFF0FACE107E5A519424" box="[1364,1392,333,356]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">str</emphasis>
.).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4875C97CFFA3FFF0FF5D10435FFB97AF" blockId="13.[151,1436,151,751]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<taxonomicName id="8FCAB2FFFFA3FFF0FF5D10435E1694C8" box="[199,311,368,392]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="7ABE156EFFA3FFF0FF5D10435E1694C8" box="[199,311,368,392]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Hydraena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is perhaps the most speciose water beetle genus (
<bibRefCitation id="2C5BB48DFFA3FFF0FCF1105C5B2594C7" author="Perkins" box="[875,1028,367,391]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" refString="Perkins, P. D. (1997). Life on the effective bubble: exocrine secretion delivery systems (ESDS) and the evolution and classification of beetles in the family Hydraenidae (Insecta: Coleoptera). Annals of Carnegie Museum, 66 (2), 89 - 207." type="journal article" year="1997">
Perkins 
<number id="FE02DB5BFFA3FFF0FC53105C5B2594C7" box="[969,1028,367,391]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="1997.0">1997</number>
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="2C5BB48DFFA3FFF0FB8A105C5BCD94C7" author="Jach" box="[1040,1260,367,391]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" refString="Jach, M. A. &amp; Balke, M. (2008). Global diversity of water beetles (Coleoptera) in freshwater. Hydrobiologia 595, 419 - 442." type="journal article" year="2008">
Jäch &amp; Balke 
<number id="FE02DB5BFFA3FFF0FB2B105C5BCD94C7" box="[1201,1260,367,391]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="2008.0">2008</number>
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="2C5BB48DFFA3FFF0FB62105C5AB194C7" author="Perkins" box="[1272,1424,367,391]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" refString="Perkins, P. D. (2011). New species (130) of the hyperdiverse aquatic beetle genus Hydraena Kugelann from Papua New Guinea, and a preliminary analysis of areas of endemism (Coleoptera: Hydraenidae). Zootaxa 2944, 1 - 417." type="journal article" year="2011">
Perkins 
<number id="FE02DB5BFFA3FFF0FACE105C5AB194C7" box="[1364,1424,367,391]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="2011.0">2011</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). Including the current contribution, the number of described species becomes about 
<number id="FE02DB5BFFA3FFF0FBF810A75BAE94EC" box="[1122,1167,404,428]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="900.0">900</number>
, but many, many more undescribed species reside in museums (
<bibRefCitation id="2C5BB48DFFA3FFF0FDFF10845C66948F" author="Jach" box="[613,839,439,463]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" refString="Jach, M. A. &amp; Balke, M. (2008). Global diversity of water beetles (Coleoptera) in freshwater. Hydrobiologia 595, 419 - 442." type="journal article" year="2008">
Jäch &amp; Balke 
<number id="FE02DB5BFFA3FFF0FC9010845C66948F" box="[778,839,439,463]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="2008.0">2008</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). The tremendous &quot;success&quot; of 
<taxonomicName id="8FCAB2FFFFA3FFF0FB35108B5A3E9490" box="[1199,1311,440,464]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="7ABE156EFFA3FFF0FB35108B5A3E9490" box="[1199,1311,440,464]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Hydraena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
appears to be, in large part, a result of the evolution of an exocrine secretion delivery system (
<collectionCode id="2EDB51B9FFA3FFF0FBA010EF5BA294B4" box="[1082,1155,476,500]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">ESDS</collectionCode>
), which is a combination of specialized cuticular structures, exocrine glands, and behavior that together function as a microbial defense system (
<bibRefCitation id="2C5BB48DFFA3FFF0FF4A13175E48977C" author="Perkins" box="[208,361,548,572]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" refString="Perkins, P. D. (1997). Life on the effective bubble: exocrine secretion delivery systems (ESDS) and the evolution and classification of beetles in the family Hydraenidae (Insecta: Coleoptera). Annals of Carnegie Museum, 66 (2), 89 - 207." type="journal article" year="1997">
Perkins 
<number id="FE02DB5BFFA3FFF0FEB713175E48977C" box="[301,361,548,572]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="1997.0">1997</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). About 
<number id="FE02DB5BFFA3FFF0FE5013175EC7977C" box="[458,486,548,572]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="50.0">50</number>
genera are currently recognized for the family. The number of species is quite modest in all but three of these genera, and only these three have an 
<collectionCode id="2EDB51B9FFA3FFF0FC1B13745CEB971F" box="[897,970,583,607]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">ESDS</collectionCode>
: 
<taxonomicName id="8FCAB2FFFFA3FFF0FC45137B5B6E9720" box="[991,1103,584,608]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="7ABE156EFFA3FFF0FC45137B5B6E9720" box="[991,1103,584,608]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Hydraena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="8FCAB2FFFFA3FFF0FBC5137B5BFF9720" box="[1119,1246,584,608]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Ochthebius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="7ABE156EFFA3FFF0FBC5137B5BFF9720" box="[1119,1246,584,608]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Ochthebius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="8FCAB2FFFFA3FFF0FABA137B5AB59720" box="[1312,1428,584,608]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Limnebius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="7ABE156EFFA3FFF0FABA137B5AB59720" box="[1312,1428,584,608]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Limnebius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName id="8FCAB2FFFFA3FFF0FF0D135F5E2697C4" box="[151,263,620,644]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="7ABE156EFFA3FFF0FF0D135F5E2697C4" box="[151,263,620,644]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Hydraena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, with perhaps 
<number id="FE02DB5BFFA3FFF0FE2B135F5EC897C4" box="[433,489,620,644]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="1000.0">1000</number>
+ species, is the largest and qualifies to be regarded as hyperdiverse (sensu 
<bibRefCitation id="2C5BB48DFFA3FFF0FAD6135F5FF597E7" author="Wilson" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" refString="Wilson, E. O. (2003). Pheidole in the new world: a dominant, hyperdiverse ant genus. Harvard University Press, Cambridge, Massachusetts. iii + 1 - 794 pp." type="book chapter" year="2003">
Wilson 
<number id="FE02DB5BFFA3FFF0FF0D13BC5FF597E7" box="[151,212,655,679]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="2003.0">2003</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). The small size of these water beetles certainly contributes to the 
<collectionCode id="2EDB51B9FFA3FFF0FC4813BC5B3697E7" box="[978,1047,655,679]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">ESDS</collectionCode>
diversity equation, through effectively limited dispersal capabilities. Many other groups of insects are tiny, and disperse poorly, but are not hyperdiverse.
</paragraph>
